# .dockerignore — keep the build context tight.
#
# Every `docker build` (or compose build) copies the full repo root as
# context before evaluating COPY directives. Without this file, that
# means uploading node_modules/, .next/, data/, and .git into the
# build daemon — many hundreds of MB on a multi-app monorepo, plus the
# risk of bleeding `data/keystore/provider.key` into a layer.

# Local dev artefacts
node_modules
**/node_modules
.pnpm-store
.pnpm-debug.log*

# Build output. Patterns without `**/` only match the repo root — and
# the .tsbuildinfo files actually live at packages/*/tsconfig.tsbuildinfo,
# so without the `**/` form tsc inside the Docker builder reads them and
# decides "nothing changed; skip" → exit 0 with empty `dist/`, then the
# next package can't find @mnela/db type declarations and the whole
# turbo run blows up. Don't relax these — empirically verified bug.
dist
build
.next
.turbo
out
*.tsbuildinfo
**/dist
**/.next
**/.turbo
**/*.tsbuildinfo

# Tests / coverage / e2e
coverage
*.lcov
.nyc_output
test-results
playwright-report
playwright/.cache

# Env / secrets (never bake into images)
.env
.env.*
!.env.example
**/.env
**/.env.*

# Runtime data (created by the running stack, never source)
data
backups
attachments
vault
dropbox
**/data
apps/api/.test-data
apps/*/data

# Git + IDE state
.git
.gitignore
.gitattributes
.github
.idea
.vscode
.cache
.tmp-*

# Test data archives that live at repo root
data-*.zip
*.tgz

# Claude Code session lock
.claude
